gth work, <em>red black and GREEN: a blues,</em> was nominated for a 2013 Bessie Award for &quot;Outstanding Production (of a work stretching the boundaries of a traditional form)&quot; and he has won numerous grants including from the National Endowment for the Arts and Creative Capital Foundation. His noted work <em>/peh-LO-tah/</em> is inspired by soccer and Bamuthi&#39;s first generation American experience, intersecting global economics, cross-border fan culture and the politics of joy.</p><p>Bamuthi is the founding Program Director of the non-profit Youth Speaks, and he is a co-founder of Life is Living, a national series of one-day festivals which activate under-resourced parks and affirm peaceful urban life. His essays have been published in Harvard Education Press; he has lectured at more than 200 colleges, has carried adjunct professorships at Stanford and Lehigh, among others, and currently serves as Chief of Program and Pedagogy at Yerba Buena Center for the Arts in San Francisco.</p>"}],"url":"https://www.ted.com/talks/marc_bamuthi_joseph_what_soccer_can_teach_us_about_freedom","viewed_count":778431,"talks":[{"recommendations":{"status":"approved","headline":"Marc Bamuthi Joseph recommends","blurb":"More resources curated by Marc Bamuthi Joseph","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":"","type":"recommendation","rec_lists":[{"title":"","description":"","rec_items":[{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*Soccer in Sun and Shadow*","blurb":"The Uruguayan author Eduardo Galeano's poetic treatise on the relationship between diplomacy, cultural idiosyncrasy and the world’s game. Among my favorite explorations of the romanticism and cross-border appeal of futbol, pulling no punches as to the local stakes of a global phenomenon.","note":"Eduardo Galeano\r\nNation Books, 2013","link_url":"https://www.amazon.com/Soccer-Sun-Shadow-Eduardo-Galeano/dp/1568584946/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"EXPLORE","headline":"M-PACT Curriculum","blurb":"","note":"Commissioned by the Guggenheim Museum, this is a guide that I wrote to accompany peh-LO-tah that might also be used independently by educators looking for new ways to catalyze both discussion and creative writing in their classrooms.","link_url":"https://www.guggenheim.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/guggenheim-m-pact-teacher-guide-2.12.18.pdf","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"READ_Article","headline":"\"Roads, Rage, Rites\"","blurb":"My recent entry to the TED Fellows blog describes how teaching my son to drive isn't just about physical mechanics, but social ones as well. His license to drive also signals his semi-permanent entry into a new classification of identity: the suspect. The two pathways of work represented in the talk and in this blog are deeply related to me ... How do we make freedom possible for youth of color? We do so through sport, through art, through political engagement, through intentional learning, through deep understanding of the circumstances of the hunted. Both these pathways represent unorthodox but logical and creative ways to access joy in the midst of struggle.","note":"Marc Bamuthi Joseph\r\nTED Fellows Blog, 2018","link_url":"https://fellowsblog.ted.com/reflections-of-a-black-father-while-teaching-his-son-to-drive-ca8a49f0454b","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":""},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"*Kindred*","blurb":"Though Octavia Butler’s first novel was published in the late 1970's and is largely set in the early 19th century, it narratively sets the tone for our contemporary understanding of the Afro-Future. I’ve been inspired by Kindred's primary protagonist, who prepares for the trauma of time travel with both physical and political survival in mind. How does an Afro-Future actually materialize without some intentional framing by creative citizens from around the diaspora? Though 